It proposes knowledge is acquired by responding to cues/operations in the environment. On the other hand, constructivism is an educational theory of learning and knowledge which states that individuals build their nouscious through experiences and interactions with their environment in order to define their own understanding of the world. 508.response_1:
Editorial on the Disadvantages of Online Education

Although online education has grown tremendously in popularity with increased access, \
its disadvantages cannot be ignored. Despite its convenience and affordability, \
online education has been criticized for its lack of face to face interaction, \
inadequate assessment and feedback, low student engagement, high dropout rates, \
low retention rates, and student isolation.

One of the main concerns of online education is the isolating alone nature it can create for students. \
Without direct contact with peers and instructors, it is often difficult to engage and get an inclusive \
sense of the classroom. Individualized feedback is also often difficult to obtain from a lecture format and \
students may have difficulty rising to the challenge of responding to the discourse of an entire course. \
Additionally, online education can be expensive in terms of a lack of interaction, less direct access to \
instructor, and having to rely on textbooks without access to discussions and library materials. 

Online instructors are also often able to assign more work that would not be the case in a traditional setting. 
This can lead to a high workload to students and in some cases exhaustion and stress. Unstructured \
freedom is another disadvantage, as some students may take shortcuts, harden their study skills, and lack motivation. \
Pie-plate assessment is also often criticized, as there are often no direct evidence of a student’s proficiencies and \
lecture videos are not considered as reliable evidence of student’s learning process. Lastly, research shows \
that there is a direct correlation between student self-awareness and confidence of their academics and this kind \
of feedback is much harder to obtain in online learning situations. 

It is important to ask the hard questions of online education, such as the disadvantages mentioned here. 
Without understanding the potential hardships of each student, it is impossible to provide the best education. 
However, effective online education must take both sides into account in order to be successful.
508.response_2:
The Pros and Cons of Online Learning: What You Didn't Know 
Online learning can be a great way to complete your degree from the comfort and ease of home, with the right resources and materials. But like with any option, there are also potential downsides to consider. For one, online learning is not yet as personal as in-class instruction, often missing out on the direct human connections, feedback, and collaborative opportunities offered in a traditional classroom setting. Additionally, online learning requires a significant amount of self-discipline, as you’re dependent entirely on your own ability to stay organized and motivated. And students may miss out on valuable hands-on or experiential learning, and the rapid pace at which most online courses are completed can be overwhelming for some students. Despite the potential downsides, online learning can be a valuable option for those looking to make the most out of their degree without the need to be physically present in a classroom.

Depth-First Search (DFS) and Breadth-First Search (BFS) are two of the most common algorithms used in graph theory. The main difference between them is that DFS explores the graph in a specific order, following a specific path. It works by looking for the closest matching node from the current node and then exploring the graph by reaching out thereafter. This means that it can read all tips of the branch out towards the leaves, though not necessarily the shortest path between two points.

BFS, however, explores the graph by levels and searches away from the starting point. This means that all vertices at a certain level are adjacent, just as all descendants at the same depth are adjacent.cestor
BFS is more efficient in terms of time complexity than DFS, but DFS has the advantage of being able to find the shortest path more quickly in a large and complex graph.

It follows a path from one node to the other in order of depth, and visits vertexes as close as possible to the highest depth. BFS on the other hand, treats the graph as a tree structure but does so by using breath first. It visits all the adjacent nodes at a certain level and then moves to the next level of depth. 1468.response_1: The Gini index is a measure used to evaluate the progress-disparity trade-off in political systems. It is calculated as the the weighted sum of the squares of the percentages of the population in each level of progressiveness from lowest to highest, except for the highest level, for which only the square of the percentage of the population is defined. For instance, if there are four levels of progressiveness, the Gini index is calculated as (P1 ^2) + (P2 ^2) + (P3 ^2) + (1 - P1 - P2 -P3) ^2          where P1, P2, P3 are the percentages of the population in each level of progressiveness.
1468.response_2: The Gini index is calculated using a weighted average of the expected values of all the leaves of a decision tree. For a given feature X with two classes, it is calculated by multiplying the fraction of leaf samples belonging to a class by the probability of picking a sample from that class. The expected value of a class is calculated as 1-A(X), where A is the fraction of leaf samples belonging to that class. The Gini index of the decision tree is then the weighted sum of all the expected values of its leaves.

The third part, precipitation, is when the water droplets or snowflakes fall from the sky.

Rules of Hangman
1. The goal of the game is to guess a word with a specific amount of guesses.

2. Each round, one letter of the word is chosen.

3. Players can guess letters. If they guess correctly, they get a hint for the next letter in the word. If they guess wrong, they get a strike.

4. When a player gets a hint, they have to guess the letter; if they get it wrong, the round is over and no one can guess the letter. That letter is then used as the hint.

5. Players can challenge each other with a letter. If the challenge is accepted, that letter is used as the hint for the round.

6. The round ends when either 5 strikes are accumulated or the players agree to end the round by revealing the letter.

7. Hunger games: At the end of each round, the players must agree on a winning letter. Players with that letter receive an additional hint for the next round.

8. Rounds can end if a certain amount of time passes or a certain amount of guesses is used.

9. The winner is the person that guesses the most letters. 

10. Players can agree on a betting system to add an extra element of excitement and competition.

1. Each player begins by thinking of a secret word. The word should contain no more than 15 letters. 
2. The first player heads up the game and leads the drawing of the hangman. The player should draw the man’s outline on a large piece of paper or on a whiteboard. 
3. The first player should then read out the secret word to other players and shake the paper so that everyone has seen it. 
4. The other players then have 3 minutes to write down their guesses for the missing letters. Each player is allowed 5 guesses, and the first person to speak up is the winner of that turn. 
5. If a small letter is guessed wrong, the Hangman is drawn. If a large letter is guessed wrong, the number of letters is more expensive. If the Hangman can be completed by guessing the correct letter, a new word is selected by the first player and the game continues. The winner of a round is the person whose guess was the most correct. 

The winner of the game is the player who has the most points when all rounds have ended. Points are awarded to players for correctly guessing secret words and for guessing letters correctly. The winner of the game is the player with the most points.

He knew that he could not receive much support from southern elected officials so he decided to take a unique approach from the public. In his memoirs, Eisenhower said that when he condemned what he saw as the "brutal abandonment of African-Americans in the South," he was largely rewarded. He was not just rewarded with this spot of support but also with the cooperation of the "majority of the southerners and northern whites" who were already over rank and tire of legislative obstructiveness.

Despite Eisenhower's relentless efforts to enfranchise African-Americans, his target of change did not come about overnight. The policy he instituted, while said to be groundbreaking, was still seen as a step too small by some. In the end, however, his mission was a success. His strong stance for civil rights was beneficial to the nation as he set great precedence for others to follow and laid the foundation for a more peaceful and equal society.

In conclusion, President Eisenhower's policy of expansive civil rights was a great success and great stride towards greater justice and equity in the United States. As the memoirs suggest, while it may have been seen as a small successes at the time, it was still beneficial overall.
